[{"id":27086,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f59531b4-2b76-4f78-88db-2a5d1da39482-image.png\" style=\"width: 252px; height: 70px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ac979fe6-4922-45b5-917f-ccecaa6baa7c-75a5f7d6-b036-4a97-9546-dd11225e947c-image.png\" style=\"width: 280px; height: 68px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e5960d99-87b9-4dbc-bb1f-d9d4620d1704-image.png\" style=\"width: 292px; height: 70px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ba3b809c-dcb6-4702-8655-8c01de014fbc-image.png\" style=\"width: 270px; height: 80px;\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Diisobutylaluminium hydride, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AlH</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Bu</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;also known as DIBAL or DIBAL-H, is an exceedingly useful and versatile reducing agent. It is an electrophilic reducing agent, usually employed in selective reductions of esters or nitriles to aldehydes</p><p>So, in first step nitrile group will be reduced to aldehyde group.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c28ff58c-e447-4e6f-acf7-c45ba8d86919-image.png\" style=\"width: 513px; height: 170px;\" /></p><p>In second step cross aldol condensation reaction will take place which will give mixture of products. Out of which one of the product will be option B.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27062,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><b>Semicarbazide</b> is the chemical compound with the formula <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OC</mi><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>)</mo><mo>(</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>)</mo></math>. It is a water-soluble white solid. It is a derivative of urea.</p><p>Acetaldehyde reacts with semicarbazide give acetaldehyde semicarbazone, the reaction will be</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/12db933e-e21c-4366-978c-cb26003abebb.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 302px;\"/></p><p>Hence the product formed has three nitrogen atoms in it.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27084,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e1716037-93dd-4fe7-af25-714197ea13e1-9893508_1.PNG\" style=\"width: 169px; height: 150px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e2f2a6b4-9b5e-40a6-804a-27538e6b66fa-9893508_2.PNG\" style=\"width: 223px; height: 150px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5512e1c6-0b86-449b-a00f-edc4a80fe5b9-9893508_3.PNG\" style=\"width: 360px; height: 94px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8ee6e327-d804-4d00-ae15-3441476984fd-9893508_4.PNG\" style=\"width: 191px; height: 92px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The cross aldol reaction takes place between isobutyraldehyde and formaldehyde&nbsp;to&nbsp;get hydroxypivaldehyde. On reaction with hydrogen cyanide&nbsp;followed by hydrolysis produces the lactone product.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/048c981b-734c-466b-af6f-d4fa7f8efab3-9893508_5.PNG\" style=\"width: 497px; height: 242px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27133,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c68b86e9-d82e-495c-8672-1501591becd2-image.png\" style=\"width: 68px; height: 65px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dbed7049-0554-4d1f-b314-686a9aa7e797-image.png\" style=\"width: 66px; height: 85px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a22d3132-d985-40ea-8598-6f5ccb781aaa-image.png\" style=\"width: 79px; height: 89px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/572536e9-8260-407f-9d99-48c7e5562af6-image.png\" style=\"width: 73px; height: 102px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The above reaction sequence is given below. In the first step, halogenation reaction is occurred then elimination reaction gives cyclohexene and reductive ozonolysis gives the dialdehyde and then aldol condensation takes place and final desired product is formed.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fc2bd8e5-de0b-42a3-a770-183d5d3d648c-image.png\" style=\"width: 723px; height: 112px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27108,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Two","One","Four","Three"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f738a834-499f-4575-8246-5722ba3af377-image.png\" style=\"width: 396px; height: 90px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27166,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Perkin reaction","Gatterman-Koch Formylation","Kolbe's reaction","Gattermann reaction"],"answer":3,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27151,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Tollen's reagent","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>NaOH</mi></math>","Alkaline&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>CS</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img height=\"78\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5261f4ad-42fb-43f1-a40f-4a70bd38af1e-image.png\" width=\"295\" /></p><p><img height=\"78\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/da217b58-6b41-41c6-bf58-92d000f5d1ff-image.png\" width=\"361\" /><br /><br />It is an iodoform reaction.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27048,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/VpNMzKqs4ld50A0oKVZufGLdpMQWao4r1JwuZHjdRc8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ckFmj8JCY1Xpye6vnzMOsh_JffiqJLliIYuVtJxcjWQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/wen4N9cKSo8BNAKPZ6egUo4yqY2xo6CXroHRVRypB9A.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ehd12r0v8QMg-Bo49BOwAukBw3d8M19nSp_ORH5CVv8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"This is Gattermann-Koch reaction\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_ppSiU_ObomiTUytxJMqDNFqG5F1QAWL9ImIYDKj0hc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27120,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn></math>-Dichlorobutane and Butanal","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn></math>-Dichlorobutane and Butan-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-one","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn></math>-Dichlorobutane and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-Butanone","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn></math>-Dichlorobutane and Butanal"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bdea5518-99a2-4ee0-a6b0-e79fe5a18132-image.png\" style=\"width: 385px; height: 126px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Aldehydes and ketones react with hydroxyl amine to form oximes but ketones do not react with Tollens reagent.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/27a1e802-29b2-4643-8047-a274c6f92412-image.png\" style=\"width: 803px; height: 186px;\" /></p><p>Compound <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><none></none><mo>&#39;</mo><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mo>&#39;</mo></mmultiscripts></math> does not gives Tollen&#39;s test due to presence of kenotic group but react with hydroxyl amine</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27018,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["$CH_2 = CH - \\overset{O}{\\underset{\\|}{C}} - OH$","$CH_3 - CH = CH - CH = O$","$O = C - OH, \\, CH_2 - OH$ (with C-C bond)","$CH_3 - \\overset{O}{\\underset{\\|}{C}} - OH$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Given the molar ratio of C, O, and H in compound $x$ is equal, the empirical formula is $CHO$.<br><br>Empirical mass $= 12 + 1 + 16 = 29$ g mol$^{-1}$.<br><br>Since the molar mass of $x$ is $58$ g mol$^{-1}$, the molecular formula is $(CHO)_2$ or $C_2H_2O_2$.<br><br>The structure of $x$ is glyoxal, $OHC-CHO$.<br><br>Treatment of glyoxal with $50\\%$ KOH under reflux results in an intramolecular Cannizzaro reaction. One aldehyde group is oxidized to a carboxylate ion, and the other is reduced to a primary alcohol.<br><br>$OHC-CHO \\xrightarrow{50\\% \\text{ KOH}} HOCH_2-COO^{-}K^{+}$<br><br>Subsequent acidification yields glycolic acid ($y$).<br><br>$HOCH_2-COO^{-}K^{+} \\xrightarrow{H^{+}} HOCH_2-COOH$<br><br>The structure of $y$ is $HO-CH_2-COOH$.<br><br>Answer: $O = C - OH, \\, CH_2 - OH$ (with C-C bond)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27158,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi>NaBH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi>ii</mi></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>Raney</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Ni</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi>iii</mi></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi>LiAlH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi>ii</mi></mfenced><mi>DIBAL</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi>iii</mi></mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi>ii</mi></mfenced><msub><mi>SnCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi>iii</mi></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c65747bf-cc3a-444c-98cd-61843da5c9f9-73aa6fe1-8722-4d3e-bae9-5d3495e1e00a-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 184px;\" /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bc1c9749-f0d0-488b-9f4e-65087f8df51b-5f62b43d-f20e-496b-b139-64437a365b8b-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 158px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27082,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true","Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true but R is NOT the correct explanation of A"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>For Assertion:&nbsp;The acetals are unstable in the presence of aqueous solutions of acid because they undergo hydrolysis in the presence of acidic conditions to produce the parent aldehyde or ketone or alcohols. But are stable and do not undergo hydrolysis in the presence of a base or under neutral conditions.</p><p>Hence assertion is correct.</p><p>For reason: Alkoxide ion <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msup><mi>RO</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo></msup><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;is not considered a good leaving group</p><p>Hence reason must be false.</p><p>So, the correct option is A</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27014,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["","","",""],"answer":2,"solution":"The reaction sequence proceeds as follows:<br><br>The reagent $\\text{NaBH}_4$ is a mild reducing agent that selectively reduces the aldehyde group ($-\\text{CHO}$) to a primary alcohol ($-\\text{CH}_2\\text{OH}$). The lactam (cyclic amide) ring remains unaffected.<br><br>Heating with aqueous $\\text{NaOH}$ causes the base-catalyzed hydrolysis of the lactam ring. The amide bond breaks, forming a carboxylate salt ($-\\text{COO}^-$) and a secondary amine ($-\\text{NH}-$).<br><br>Acidification with $\\text{H}_3\\text{O}^+$ protonates the carboxylate ion to form a carboxylic acid ($-\\text{COOH}$).<br><br>The final product is an open-chain amino acid derivative with the structure $\\text{HOOC}-\\text{CH}_2-\\text{CH}_2-\\text{CH}_2-\\text{CH}_2-\\text{NH}-\\text{CH(CH}_3)-\\text{CH}_2\\text{OH}$. This matches the structure given in option (C).<br><br>Answer:","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (08 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27096,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fe741bd1-8e0b-4177-8e0a-58d4edd73de6-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 109px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8f108d57-86dd-44ce-88b8-d1a7f1c4a90e-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 115px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/66c856b2-5a05-4b81-8ece-fea8e98ed311-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 116px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2d5c61e4-5007-4b43-91b3-8d8cdb7cceca-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 113px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6a233f28-586e-4530-8039-d2761354080c-9709524_Solution.png\" style=\"width: 550px; height: 365px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27094,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"In an aldol condensation, an enolate ion reacts with a carbonyl compound in the presence of acid/base catalyst to form a &beta;-hydroxy aldehyde or &beta;-hydroxy ketone, followed by dehydration to give a conjugated enone. It is a useful carbon-carbon bond-forming reaction.<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b59c8e8e-e6b3-4da4-aee5-6f80f033991a-9711756_2.png\" style=\"width: 550px; height: 185px;\" /></p><p>As there are 2 pi bonds in the major product(P), the number of pi electrons will be equal to 4.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27132,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f5309140-778f-4e29-8908-17cf027c27b1-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 82px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0c299e5c-7181-446d-b5c7-f0e0395c5201-image.png\" style=\"width: 179px; height: 87px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c4692c5a-1be7-4b30-bc70-a482980e703f-image.png\" style=\"width: 134px; height: 83px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bc16f9ff-8214-46f8-b306-ddeb6b6e8943-image.png\" style=\"width: 179px; height: 89px;\" />&nbsp;"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e222b351-8eba-4759-9812-71d66ba83caf-image.png\" style=\"width: 544px; height: 340px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HBr</mi></math>&nbsp;attacks on given molecule and provides product in which&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi></math>&nbsp;group is attached at two sites (one is substitution and another is addition on alkene ) and it is followed by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;elimination and provides alkene which gives aldehyde on ozonolysis.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27069,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c7194914-d521-4fad-8c28-fabb7804eba0-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 114px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eadbee56-84ea-4ca3-b4d1-2fe7d2032a83-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 82px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3173c903-390f-4c68-ad5d-60f31520c119-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 90px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d6326125-6f32-40ea-9456-2cdb7f7f160f-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 109px;\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Oxidation of this substituted ketone will give a ketone and&nbsp;a&nbsp;carboxylic acid. This reaction takes place by the cleavage of carbon atoms near the carbonyl carbon and the nearby carbons. This cleavage can be from both the sides of carbonyl carbon thus producing two different carboxylic acids and ketones. The ketone formed converts to hydrocarbon in the presence hydrazine in alkaline medium. The overall reaction is shown below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e2011e02-5da3-4548-8957-f5e107a9dacb-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 372px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27058,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Stephen reaction","Etard reaction","Gatterman-koch reaction","Rosenmund reduction"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Gattermann – Koch reaction is used for the industrial production of benzaldehyde. </p><p>In Gattermann – Koch reaction, benzene is treated with carbon monoxide in the acidic medium in presence of anhydrous aluminium chloride to give benzaldehyde. In this reaction, anhydrous aluminium chloride works as a catalyst. It is an electrophilic substitution reaction.<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aa7eeb78-cb04-4862-a172-6589570c1d9e.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 183px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27042,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["(A)-(I), (B)-(IV), (C)-(III), (D)-(II)","(A)-(III), (B)-(II), (C)-(I), (D)-(IV)","(A)-(III), (B)-(IV), (C)-(I), (D)-(II)","(A)-(II), (B)-(III), (C)-(I), (D)-(IV)"],"answer":2,"solution":"Ozonolysis product\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7p3hueXp5Gh2M62UqhmWRgBudUR6pSLY05U64Ms5ALs.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27178,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["propene","1-butene","2-butene","ethene"],"answer":2,"solution":"2-butene is symmetrical alkene\n$\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}=\\mathrm{CH}-\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\frac{\\mathrm{O}_3}{\\mathrm{Zn} / \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}} 2 \\cdot 2 \\cdot \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CHO}$\nMolar mass of $\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CHO}$ is $44 \\mathrm{u}$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":27024,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["2-hydroxy acetophenone","4-methyl benzoic acid","4-methoxy benzaldehyde","4-hydroxy benzaldehyde"],"answer":2,"solution":"<br>(On cross aldol reaction, a single structure is obtained but it can show geometrical isomerism).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27021,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A, C & E Only","B, D & E Only","A & C Only","A, B & C Only"],"answer":2,"solution":"In the haloform reaction:<br><b>(A)</b> Sodium hypochlorite reacts with KI in acidic medium to generate the active halogenating species, forming KOI (potassium iodite/hypoidite). TRUE.<br><b>(B)</b> KOI serves as an oxidizing agent (not reducing) in the reaction, converting methyl ketones to carboxylic acids. FALSE.<br><b>(C)</b> $α,β$-unsaturated methylketones possess the essential methyl ketone group ($CH_3CO-$) required for haloform reaction, allowing iodination and subsequent cleavage. TRUE.<br><b>(D)</b> Isopropyl alcohol $(CH_3)_2CHOH$ lacks a methyl ketone group, so it cannot undergo the haloform reaction. TRUE.<br><b>(E)</b> Formic acid has no methyl ketone functionality, preventing haloform test. FALSE.<br>Therefore, statements A and C are true.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27100,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<p>(a)</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d30191fd-dd66-45ba-9d36-880827b88be6-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 103px;\" /></p><p>(b)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p>","<p>(a)</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5a74c46c-b41f-4963-8a78-c12d94e3fe2f-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 109px;\" /></p><p>(b)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>PCC</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>DCM</mi></math></p>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c8de58c9-1dcd-4a9c-b9fe-86642d36894e-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 90px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bcc5a3fd-445f-42ae-8e9f-344cfc2be5dc-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 83px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Ethyl benzoate on reaction with 2 moles of grignard reagent forms a tertiary alcohol.Hence acetophenone cannot be formed in this reaction as shown below.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ph</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>COO</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi><mo>&#10230;</mo><msub><mi>PhCOCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi></mrow></mover><mi>PhC</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27074,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"No reaction with strong base or acid indicates presence of strong neutrality or non-reactive functional hroup with a single oxygen. No positive 2,4-DNP test indicates absence of carbonyl compound. Same compound formation upon hydrogenation indicates single double bond. Thus, it is an ether.<br /><br />As per the language of given question, the best possible isomeric structure is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ph</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;(cis and trans). So, the answer is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27110,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7ca47d7c-e5d1-4a54-8aeb-54573a3f3081-image.png\" style=\"width: 161px; height: 114px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1e146739-666f-444b-8d28-8366dde02716-image.png\" style=\"width: 167px; height: 119px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/69e40b18-5424-49d1-a8e8-476e55d8079f-image.png\" style=\"width: 176px; height: 114px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f85c36e6-f048-4198-ac76-923e2ebdf4e6-image.png\" style=\"width: 190px; height: 116px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7be6569c-55a8-4189-b479-82571dc5f076-image.png\" style=\"width: 538px; height: 389px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27123,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d594ad72-9c50-4818-b22d-098121548b9b-image.png\" style=\"width: 129px; height: 51px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fdc7f480-0d9f-461e-a7f0-c2ec02383ec9-image.png\" style=\"width: 127px; height: 52px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/93957510-13ab-494b-9934-1be605e039d8-image.png\" style=\"width: 86px; height: 47px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dc37c9f1-b094-4856-8164-c5547684c7ee-image.png\" style=\"width: 139px; height: 66px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Reaction of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>HgSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>dil</mi><mo>.</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> with alkyne gives addition of water as per markonikoff&#39;s rule.</p><p><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CH</mi><mo>&#8801;</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><munderover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>HgSO</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo></mrow></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></munderover><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi></math></p><p>Hence, by this process preparation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi></math><br />Cann&#39;t possible.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6391ae6b-79ce-4cdd-8a41-a0ac1353c588-ascaa.png\" style=\"width: 429px; height: 348px;\" /></p><p>Hence <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>CHO</mi></math> cannot be formed.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3278593f-7584-4df0-acef-3c68916d624a-image.png\" style=\"width: 351px; height: 159px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27046,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bvx7GoFyFIhPoII92puMR-dGrYccy3mLIZ9RlpleXKk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/DqlLWnhqyxM6JX4tama1O6VL4mIW7vk1mv-2mLpje2c.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/UgdOEl-mB4ZwyB6IoaCzDjTsd1Ju3bbkOdstKcxTiNk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","\\(\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CHO}\\)"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4tAwID7Lfwtr1xmhTV3OMlMbfsDIBOmvx1aVlkPeeZw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27136,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>≈</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>≈</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>≈</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>≈</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>≈</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>d</mi><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>P</mi><msub><mrow><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi>C</mi><msub><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi>P</mi><msup><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>  <br/><math><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>N</mi><mi>i</mi><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>O</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi>N</mi><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>F</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>  <br/><math><msup><mrow><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>N</mi><mi>i</mi><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>N</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> <math><mi>N</mi><msup><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>F</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> <math><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>  <br/><math><msup><mrow><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>N</mi><mi>i</mi><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi>O</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> <math><mi>N</mi><msup><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>W</mi><mi>F</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> <math><msubsup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><mtext> </mtext><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><mtext> </mtext><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><msubsup><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><mtext> </mtext><mn>1</mn></mrow></msubsup></math> So, unpaired electron is <math><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>8</mn></msqrt><mi></mi><mi>B</mi><mi>M</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27144,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"220\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2483b613-08e0-46ac-a291-66c40310abd2-image.png\" width=\"337\" /></p><p><img height=\"220\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8cfed5ea-fdcd-409d-839c-fce99f947476-image.png\" width=\"336\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/95cfd0e8-14e7-4279-90ca-18a57b754a57-image.png\" style=\"width: 459px; height: 156px;\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"215\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7a8196df-a5c6-4a45-b91e-ca4bc274f8c1-image.png\" width=\"336\" /></p><p><img height=\"215\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/174d423d-a729-4b75-8234-251e6ce7973a-image.png\" width=\"337\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"159\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ed34ba5c-0a79-4803-bf3c-cc7c1d90d76d-image.png\" width=\"463\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>This is an intramolecular aldol condensation reaction.</p><p><img height=\"100\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/72600d96-01f8-44e0-b1ee-9b2a393deeef-image.png\" width=\"424\" /></p><p><img height=\"137\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/360c20ab-6cb3-4d9a-9617-0819d1e9e9ab-image.png\" width=\"379\" /></p><p><img height=\"107\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/903e68a9-d5ea-416a-b71f-85cdedcd5ff6-image.png\" width=\"450\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27060,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/247cf632-875e-4c2c-ba49-a3c9cbd6608e.png\" style=\"width: 315px; height: 185px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ebf5247a-0d4f-4c84-9b7f-70eb808c531f.png\" style=\"width: 401px; height: 180px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/be766da0-d965-496e-a925-6e58e5db6ddf.png\" style=\"width: 351px; height: 158px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/12114879-7dfb-44a0-a97e-210fd170e723.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 182px;\"/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Meta–chlorobenzaldehyde will undergo Cannizzaro reaction with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo>%</mo><mo> </mo><mi>KOH</mi></math> to give mchlorobenzoate ion and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>-</mo></math>chlorobenzyl alcohol. </p><p>Since <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>-</mo></math>chlorobenzaldehyde does not contain α hydrogen thus with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo>%</mo><mo> </mo><mi>KOH</mi></math> it undergoes the Cannizzaro reaction. The Cannizzaro reaction for the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>-</mo></math>chlorobenzaldehyde is given as:</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/50073db2-f5e4-463e-adf9-af7f4a4d5472.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 156px;\"/>Since it is a disproportionation reaction so one molecule of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>-</mo></math>chlorobenzaldehyde is reduced to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>-</mo></math>chlorobenzyl alcohol at the cost of others which is oxidized potassium <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>-</mo></math>chlorobenzoate.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null}]